---
// src/components/overlays/MarsOverlay.astro — Labs / Experiments
// 8 sections — layout data-attributes drive CSS positioning.
// Sections match MARS_SCROLL_PATH waypoints in PlanetScrollCameras.ts.

const items = [
  {
    id:       'terrarium',
    category: 'EXPERIMENT',
    title:    'Terrarium',
    meta:     'WebGL + GLSL · 2024',
    body: [
      'A generative plant-growth shader — one rule (branches bend toward the brightest point on screen) run thousands of times to see what shapes emerge without any single stroke being hand-drawn. The constraint was strict: no pre-baked geometry, everything grown in the fragment shader from a single seed value.',
      'The first version grew nothing but straight lines — the "bend toward light" rule needed noise injected into the branching angle before anything resembling a plant showed up. The failure taught more about how organic-looking randomness actually works than the eventual success did.',
      'Currently a standalone WebGL demo, not wired into anything production. Turning it into a generative loading-screen background is the obvious next step, not yet done.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Rule', 'What Failed First', 'Where It Stands'],
  },
  {
    id:       'echograph',
    category: 'EXPERIMENT',
    title:    'Echograph',
    meta:     'Web Audio API · 2023',
    body: [
      'A real-time audio visualiser that reacts to frequency data from the Web Audio API instead of a canned animation — feed it any playing audio and it draws a live waveform field that actually reflects what is playing, bass and treble rendered as different depths in a 3D scene.',
      'The unexpected result: silence turned out to be the hardest case to handle gracefully, not loud audio. A flat frequency spectrum produced a visually dead scene, which meant designing an idle-state animation that only kicks in below a volume threshold.',
      'This is the project that proved audio-reactive visuals were worth the effort — a version of this exact technique now drives the hover sound feedback across this site\'s UI.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Setup', 'The Surprise', 'What It Shows'],
  },
  {
    id:       'fracture',
    category: 'EXPERIMENT',
    title:    'Fracture',
    meta:     'Canvas + Physics · 2023',
    body: [
      'A shatter effect for UI elements — click a card and it breaks into physically-simulated shards that fall and settle under gravity, instead of the usual fade-and-slide dismissal. Built with a lightweight 2D physics step written from scratch rather than a full physics engine, since the use case never needed collision resolution beyond "fall and stop."',
      'Building this revealed a real limitation of Canvas 2D: redrawing hundreds of independently-rotating shard polygons every frame is fine at low counts and falls off a cliff past roughly 150 shards on mid-range hardware — the kind of ceiling that only shows up once you actually stress-test past the demo case.',
      'Status: archived as a component, but the shard-fracture math got reused (rewritten for WebGL instancing) in an early prototype of this site\'s warp transition before the current starfield approach replaced it.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Medium', 'What It Revealed', 'Current Status'],
  },
  {
    id:       'driftwood',
    category: 'EXPERIMENT',
    title:    'Driftwood',
    meta:     'Three.js + Verlet Physics · 2022',
    body: [
      'A cloth/rope simulation built on Verlet integration, applied to something deliberately unglamorous: a driftwood-and-rope bridge that sways believably under a simulated wind force. No practical use case going in — just curiosity about whether a from-scratch physics step could look convincing without a physics engine dependency.',
      'What makes this one different from the others: it is the only experiment here that is pure simulation, no visual shader trickery. If Terrarium and Fracture are about rendering, Driftwood is about the underlying math holding up on its own.',
      'Eleven iterations before the rope stopped visibly vibrating at rest — the real lesson was about numerical damping, not about Three.js. The kind of problem that looks like a rendering bug but is actually a math bug.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Outlier', 'Technique vs. Concept', 'The Real Lesson'],
  },
];
